 insecurity is experienced, what people consider existential threats, and how they go about securing themselves. It concentrates on individuals who feel threatened because of their ethnic belonging, gender or sexual orientation. It develops the concept of ‘securityscapes’, which draws attention to the more subtle means that people take to secure themselves – practices bent on invisibility and avoidance, on disguise and trickery, and on continually adapting to shifting circumstances. By broadening the concept of security practice, this book is an important contribution to debates in Critical Security Studies as well as to Central Asian and Area Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aAsankanov, Abylabek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtakhanov, Shavkat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBagdasarova, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBagdasarova, Nina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoboyorov, Hafiz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsmailbekova, Aksana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsmailbekova, Aksana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKorschinek, Anna M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyrzabekova, Asel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOestmann, Kathrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchetter, Conrad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchetter, Conrad, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 avon Boemcken, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.